(SECTION 1: FAFSA AND FEDERAL AID BASICS) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(The FAFSA is the Free Application for Federal Student Aid. It is often the) Tj
T*
(first step students take before they apply for grants, loans, and many) Tj
T*
(scholarships. For this workshop sample, students should aim for a priority) Tj
T*
(filing date of March 1 for the next academic year. The federal FAFSA deadline) Tj
T*
(is listed here as June 30 at the end of the award year. Schools and states may) Tj
T*
(use earlier priority dates, so students should always verify the real deadline) Tj
T*
(with official sources.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Students may qualify for federal aid even if they do not think of themselves) Tj
T*
(as "financial aid students." Completing the FAFSA can open access to Pell) Tj
T*
(Grants, work-study, subsidized loans, and some campus-based emergency support) Tj
T*
(funds.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(SECTION 2: PELL GRANT SNAPSHOT) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(The Pell Grant is a federal grant for undergraduate students with financial) Tj
T*
(need. In this workshop sample, Pell Grant awards are described as need-based) Tj
T*
(and do not need to be repaid if the student remains eligible. Award amounts) Tj
T*
(vary by year, enrollment status, and Student Aid Index rules in effect for) Tj
T*
(that cycle.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Students should know three things about Pell Grants:) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(- They usually require a completed FAFSA) Tj
T*
(- Part-time students may still qualify, but the amount can be lower) Tj
T*
(- Pell Grant eligibility can help a student qualify for additional campus or) Tj
T*
(  nonprofit aid) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(SECTION 3: HISPANIC SCHOLARSHIP FUND) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(The Hispanic Scholarship Fund, or HSF, supports students of Hispanic heritage) Tj
T*
(pursuing undergraduate or graduate education. In this workshop sample, the) Tj
T*
(scholarship application opens in January and uses a sample deadline of) Tj
T*
(February 15.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
